ntary research orders -- t17 Sir Robert Cotton as archival research assistant to government and Parliament -- t18 John Selden: Archival research, legal history, and constitutional activism -- t19 William Prynne and the counter-revolution in the records editions -- t20 Epilogue to Part Two: The Civil War, the Tower records clerks, and espionage -- tPart Three: Secrecy and Access at the State Paper Office -- t21 Thomas Wilson’s appointment as Keeper: The political background -- t22 The establishment of the State Paper Office -- t23 Francis Bacon, George Villiers, and records classification -- t24 Practical problems at the State Paper Office: Records storage, Jacobean court intrigues, and money matters -- t25 The political uses of history and the Crown’s records -- t26 Records accessioning and power politics during Wilson’s tenure -- t27 Archives and intrigue: Wilson and the judicial persecution of Sir Walter Ralegh -- t28 The State Paper Office after Wilson -- t29 The Civil War and Interregnum -- t30 The Restoration, records seizures from Revolutionaries, and cataloguing -- t31 Official secrecy and research permissions -- t32 Use requests under James I -- t33 Use requests after the Restoration -- tConclusion: English archives and the wider European context -- tBibliography -- tBiographical note -- tIndex of Persons0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aArchives are popularly seen as liminal, obscure spaces -- a perception far removed from the early modern reality. This examination of the central English archival system in the period before 1700 highlights the role played by the public records repositories in furnishing precedents for the constitutional struggle between Crown and Parliament. It traces the deployment of archival research in these controversies by three individuals who were at various points occupied with the keeping of records: Sir Robert Cotton, John Selden, and William Prynne. The book concludes by investigating the secretive State Paper Office, home of the arcana imperii, and its involvement in the government's intelligence network: notably the engagement of its most prominent Keeper Sir Thomas Wilson in judicial and political intrigue on behalf of the Crown.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aArchivgeschichte Englands. 4aPolitische Geschichte Englands. 4aVerfassungsgeschichte Englands. 7aHISTORY / Modern / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG0 cEPUBz97831107915630 cprintz978311079126640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311079146440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110791464423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110791464/original  a978-3-11-131913-1  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2023  aZDB-23-DGGb2023